nds"]}, {"title": "Music Technology with a focus on Music Information Retrieval (MIR)", "reason": "This major combines the student''s passion for music with coding skills, offering a unique opportunity to work on music analysis, recommendation systems, and audio processing.", "pros": ["Interdisciplinary approach combining music and technology", "Potential for innovative applications in the music industry"], "cons": ["Niche field with limited job openings", "Requires advanced mathematical and programming skills"]}]', '{"S1_TheEvent": "A", "S2_TheVariety": "B", "S3_TheInfluence": "A", "S4_TheNewcomer": "B", "S5_TheBrainstorm": "A"}', 'The conversation reveals the student''s interest in exploring the intersection of technology and entertainment, with a focus on user experience and feedback. This suggests a potential aptitude for careers in software development, user interface design, or audio technology.', '{"skipped": true, "flow": "simplified"}', '{}', 'Technology & Innovation', 'The student exhibits a strong inclination towards combining creative and logical pursuits, indicating a versatile and adaptive approach to problem-solving. Their enthusiasm for music, sports, and coding suggests a dynamic and innovative mindset.', '[{"title": "Computer Science with a focus on Audio Technology", "reason": "This major aligns with the student''s interest in coding and music, offering a pathway to develop innovative audio applications.", "pros": ["Opportunities for creative problem-solving", "Growing demand for audio technology specialists"], "cons": ["Highly competitive field", "Continuous need for updating skills"]}, {"title": "Software Engineering with a specialization in User Experience (UX) Design", "reason": "This career path leverages the student''s coding skills and interest in user feedback, providing a route to design engaging and user-friendly applications.", "pros": ["Combines technical and creative skills", "High demand for UX designers in the tech industry"], "cons": ["Requires strong understanding of human-computer interaction principles", "Constantly evolving design trends"]}, {"title": "Music Technology with a focus on Music Information Retrieval (MIR)", "reason": "This major combines the student''s passion for music with coding skills, offering a unique opportunity to work on music analysis, recommendation systems, and audio processing.", "pros": ["Interdisciplinary approach combining music and technology", "Potential for innovative applications in the music industry"], "cons": ["Niche field with limited job openings", "Requires advanced mathematical and programming skills"]}]', '[]', 'Software Engineering with a specialization in User Experience (UX) Design', '["You''ve discovered that a new feature you designed for a client has a significant flaw that could compromise user data, but fixing it would delay the project and potentially lose the client; what do you do?", "You''re on a tight deadline to deliver a critical UX design component, but your team''s backend engineer is running behind schedule, and the project lead is breathing down your neck; how do you handle the situation?", "A team member has strongly disagreed with your design approach, citing that it''s not user-friendly, and the discussion is becoming heated; how do you resolve the conflict and find a solution that works for everyone?", "Your last UX design project received negative feedback from users, and the client is considering terminating the contract; what steps would you take to recover from this failure and improve the design?", "You''re considering a job offer from a company that aligns with your long-term career goals, but it would require relocating to a new city and potentially disrupting your personal life; what factors would you consider when making this decision?", "A stakeholder requests a design change that contradicts best practices for user experience, citing that it''s what their competitor is doing; how would you approach this situation and what would you say to the stakeholder?", "You''re tasked with designing a new mobile app for a company, but their existing brand guidelines are outdated and not optimized for digital platforms; how would you balance the need to adhere to the existing brand identity with the need to create a modern and user-friendly digital experience?"]', '[]', NULL),
	(52, 57, 'Dynamic Generalist', 'Ambivert', 'Goal Aware', 0.8897164682276509, 'The user''s classification as a Dynamic Generalist is validated through their preference for collaborative environments, ability to handle multiple roles, and tendency to analyze and solve problems quietly. Their goal-oriented approach, as evident from their desire to create a big impact, and their willingness to take calculated risks, further supports this archetype. The user''s ambivert personality and goal-aware status are inferred from their balanced approach to social interactions and clear career aspirations.', '{"Ultimate goal?": "Main change aur big impact create karna chahta hoon", "Best problem solver kaun hota hai?": "Jo silently analyze aur solve kare", "Tumhe kaunsa learning environment suit karta hai?": "Collaborative environment", "Agar aapko confusion ho career me, aap kya karoge?": "Ek field choose karke usme stick rahunga", "Kaam start karne ka style?": "Main situation observe karke phir quietly action leta hoon", "Agar koi event organize karna ho toh tum?": "Multiple roles handle karta hoon", "Tum zyada kis type ke decisions lete ho?": "Well-planned aur structured", "Understanding style?": "Main alag-alag areas mein knowledge build karta hoon", "Tum feedback kaise lete ho?": "Apne kaam ko improve karne ke liye deeply analyze karta hoon", "Creative ideas mein risk lene par tumhara approach kya hai?": "High-risk ideas try karta hoon"}', '12th', '[{"title": "Counseling Psychology", "reason": "It fits because the student values friendships and human connection, which are essential in counseling psychology.", "pros": ["Opportunities for personal growth", "Helping others"], "cons": ["Emotional demands", "Continuous education requirements"]}, {"title": "Social Work", "reason": "It fits because the student thinks outside the box and may be drawn to careers that involve creative problem-solving and community engagement.", "pros": ["Variety of work settings", "Opportunities for advocacy"], "cons": ["High stress levels", "Emotional burnout"]}, {"title": "Education (Teaching or Administration)", "reason": "It fits because the student''s ability to think outside the box could be an asset in educational settings, where creativity and adaptability are valued.", "pros": ["Opportunities for mentorship", "Shaping young minds"], "cons": ["Classroom management challenges", "Standardized testing pressures"]}]', NULL, 'The student''s interests are not explicitly stated, but their love for a friend and desire for human connection imply a need for careers that prioritize interpersonal relationships and community building.', '{"skipped": true, "flow": "simplified"}', '{}', 'Social Sciences & Humanities', 'The student''s professional outlook is uncertain due to their distress and eagerness for recommendations. However, their ability to think outside the box and value friendships suggests a potential for careers that involve creativity, empathy, and social interaction.', '[{"title": "Counseling Psychology", "reason": "It fits because the student values friendships and human connection, which are essential in counseling psychology.", "pros": ["Opportunities for personal growth", "Helping others"], "cons": ["Emotional demands", "Continuous education requirements"]}, {"title": "Social Work", "reason": "It fits because the student thinks outside the box and may be drawn to careers that involve creative problem-solving and community engagement.", "pros": ["Variety of work settings", "Opportunities for advocacy"], "cons": ["High stress levels", "Emotional burnout"]}, {"title": "Education (Teaching or Administration)", "reason": "It fits because the student''s ability to think outside the box could be an asset in educational settings, where creativity and adaptability are valued.", "pros": ["Opportunities for mentorship", "Shaping young minds"], "cons": ["Classroom management challenges", "Standardized testing pressures"]}]', NULL, 'Education (Teaching or Administration)', '["You are a school administrator and have discovered that a beloved teacher has been falsifying student grades to improve the school''s overall academic standing. What do you do?", "You have just been informed that the school''s budget is being cut by 20% and you must decide which programs to eliminate by the end of the day. How do you handle this high-pressure situation?", "A conflict arises between two teachers with fundamentally different instructional methods, causing tension among students and staff. How do you facilitate a resolution and foster a collaborative work environment?", "You implemented a new educational program that, despite your best efforts, failed to yield the desired results. How do you recover from this setback and what changes would you make moving forward?", "You are considering a job offer as a superintendent of a nearby school district, but it would require you to relocate and leave behind your current school community. What factors do you consider when making this long-term decision?", "You are tasked with developing a plan to address the growing achievement gap between students from different socioeconomic backgrounds. What strategies would you employ to ensure equitable access to quality education for all students?", "You are faced with a situation where a parent is disputing a grade their child received, claiming that the teacher made an error. How do you navigate this situation while maintaining a positive relationship with the parent and upholding the teacher''s professional judgment?"]', '["his is a tough situation because it involves ethics, trust, and student futures\u2014not just school reputation. As an administrator, you have to act firmly but fairly.\r\n\r\nHere\u2019s the right approach step by step:\r\n\r\n1. Verify the Facts (No Assumptions)\r\n\r\nBefore taking action, gather clear evidence:\r\n\r\nCheck grade records, exam papers, and discrepancies\r\nCompare internal vs external assessment data\r\nSpeak confidentially with relevant staff if needed\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 You must be 100% sure before accusing a teacher of something this serious.\r\n\r\n2. Have a Private Conversation with the Teacher\r\nMeet the teacher confidentially\r\nPresent the evidence calmly and professionally\r\nGive them a chance to explain\r\n\r\nSometimes there may be pressure, misunderstanding, or systemic issues\u2014but falsifying grades is still a major violation.\r\n\r\n3. Follow Institutional Policy\r\nReport the issue to higher authorities (principal/board)\r\nFollow disciplinary procedures as per school rules\r\nDocument everything properly\r\n\r\nThis ensures fairness and legal protection for both the school and the teacher.\r\n\r\n4. Correct the Academic Records\r\nIdentify all affected students\r\nRestore accurate grades based on real performance\r\nInform stakeholders (students/parents) carefully and transparently\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This step is critical because students\u2019 futures (college admissions, careers) may be impacted.\r\n\r\n5. Take Appropriate Disciplinary Action\r\n\r\nDepending on severity and policy:\r\n\r\nWarning or suspension\r\nMandatory training\r\nTermination in serious cases\r\n\r\nEven if the teacher is \u201cbeloved,\u201d integrity cannot be compromised.\r\n\r\n6. Address Root Causes\r\n\r\nAsk:\r\n\r\nWas there pressure to improve results?\r\nAre teachers being judged unfairly based on scores?\r\n\r\nThen:\r\n\r\nImprove evaluation systems\r\nPromote ethical practices\r\nProvide teacher support instead of pressure\r\n7. Rebuild Trust\r\nReinforce academic honesty across the school\r\nConduct audits periodically\r\nCommunicate values clearly: integrity > rankings\r\nKey Principle\r\n\r\nA school\u2019s reputation should be built on real learning, not manipulated results. Protecting students\u2019 trust and fairness matters more than short-term success.", "This is a high-pressure leadership and decision-making scenario, so the key is to show calm prioritization, fairness, and student-first thinking\u2014not panic cuts.\r\n\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Stay Calm and Clarify the Situation\r\nConfirm the exact 20% reduction amount and what areas it affects\r\nUnderstand fixed vs flexible costs (salaries, infrastructure vs programs)\r\nIdentify if the cut is temporary or long-term\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Quick clarity prevents wrong decisions under pressure.\r\n\r\n2. Define Clear Decision Criteria\r\n\r\nBefore cutting anything, set fair criteria:\r\n\r\nImpact on student learning (highest priority)\r\nNumber of students affected\r\nProgram outcomes/results\r\nCost vs benefit\r\nAvailability of alternatives\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This ensures decisions are objective, not emotional or biased.\r\n\r\n3. Protect Core Academic Functions\r\nSafeguard essential subjects and teaching staff\r\nMaintain student safety and basic operations\r\nAvoid cuts that directly harm academic foundation\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 The goal is to protect learning continuity first.\r\n\r\n4. Identify Areas for Reduction\r\n\r\nInstead of immediately eliminating programs:\r\n\r\nLook for cost optimizations (reduce materials, renegotiate vendors)\r\nTemporarily pause low-impact or low-participation programs\r\nMerge or restructure overlapping activities\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Cut waste before value.\r\n\r\n5. Take Quick but Inclusive Input\r\n\r\nEven with limited time:\r\n\r\nConsult key staff or department heads briefly\r\nGet rapid insights on program importance\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This improves decision quality and builds trust.\r\n\r\n6. Make the Decision Transparently\r\nChoose programs to pause/eliminate based on criteria\r\nDocument the reasoning clearly\r\nEnsure fairness across departments\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Transparency reduces resistance and confusion.\r\n\r\n7. Communicate Effectively\r\nInform teachers, students, and parents honestly\r\nEmphasize that decisions were made to protect core education\r\nAcknowledge impact and show empathy\r\n8. Plan for Recovery\r\nMark programs as \u201ctemporarily paused\u201d where possible\r\nExplore alternative funding (grants, partnerships, sponsorships)\r\nCreate a roadmap to reintroduce valuable programs later\r\nKey Principle\r\n\r\nIn high-pressure situations, a strong leader:\r\n\r\nStays calm\r\nUses structured decision-making\r\nProtects what matters most (students\u2019 learning)\r\nCommunicates with honesty and empathy", "This is a people-management and conflict-resolution scenario. The goal isn\u2019t to pick a \u201cbetter\u201d teaching style\u2014it\u2019s to restore collaboration and keep students\u2019 learning at the center.\r\n\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Understand the Root Cause (Individually First)\r\nMeet each teacher privately\r\nLet them explain their perspective without interruption\r\nIdentify the real issue: teaching philosophy, communication gaps, or personal friction\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This prevents escalation and shows respect to both sides.\r\n\r\n2. Focus on the Common Goal\r\nReframe the situation: \u201cWe all want the best outcomes for students.\u201d\r\nShift the discussion from \u201cwho is right\u201d \u2192 \u201cwhat works best for students\u201d\r\n3. Facilitate a Structured Joint Meeting\r\nBring both teachers together in a neutral setting\r\nSet ground rules: respect, no interruptions, solution-focused dialogue\r\nEncourage each to explain their method and its benefits\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This creates mutual understanding instead of assumptions.\r\n\r\n4. Find Middle Ground (Blended Approach)\r\nIdentify strengths in both instructional styles\r\nExplore ways to combine approaches where possible\r\ne.g., one uses interactive learning, the other structured lectures \u2192 blend both\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 The aim is collaboration, not compromise at the cost of quality.\r\n\r\n5. Create Clear Agreements\r\nDefine expectations moving forward:\r\nCommunication norms\r\nClassroom boundaries (if they share students)\r\nConsistency in student messaging\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Clarity prevents future misunderstandings.\r\n\r\n6. Support with Professional Development\r\nSuggest workshops, peer observations, or co-teaching opportunities\r\nEncourage them to learn from each other instead of competing\r\n7. Monitor and Follow Up\r\nCheck in regularly with both teachers and students\r\nAddress any recurring issues early\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Conflict resolution is not one-time\u2014it needs follow-through.\r\n\r\n8. Foster a Collaborative Culture\r\nPromote open dialogue among staff\r\nEncourage sharing of best practices\r\nRecognize teamwork, not just individual performance\r\nKey Principle\r\n\r\nDifferent teaching styles can actually be a strength, not a problem\u2014if managed well.\r\nA good leader turns conflict into an opportunity for innovation and collaboration.", "This is a leadership, accountability, and learning-from-failure scenario. The strongest response shows that you own the outcome, learn quickly, and improve the system.\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Take Responsibility (No Blame Game)\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledge that the program didn\u2019t meet expectations\r\n\r\n\r\nCommunicate honestly with staff and stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This builds trust and credibility as a leader.\r\n\r\n2. Analyze What Went Wrong\r\nConduct a structured review:\r\n\r\n\r\nWere the goals unrealistic or unclear?\r\n\r\n\r\nWas there a gap in execution or training?\r\n\r\n\r\nDid we ignore student needs or feedback?\r\n\r\n\r\nWere there resource or time constraints?\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Use data: student performance, feedback, participation rates.\r\n\r\n3. Gather Feedback from All Stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\nTeachers: challenges in implementation\r\n\r\n\r\nStudents: engagement and learning experience\r\n\r\n\r\nParents (if relevant): observed impact\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This gives a 360\u00b0 understanding, not just assumptions.\r\n\r\n4. Identify Key Learnings\r\nConvert failure into insights:\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat worked (keep it)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat didn\u2019t (fix or remove)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat was missing (add it)\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Failure becomes valuable data, not wasted effort.\r\n\r\n5. Make Targeted Improvements\r\n\r\n\r\nRedesign the program based on insights\r\n\r\n\r\nProvide better training/support to teachers\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust content, pacing, or delivery methods\r\n\r\n\r\nStart with a pilot program before full rollout\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Move from trial \u2192 refined strategy.\r\n\r\n6. Re-Implement in Phases\r\n\r\n\r\nTest improvements on a smaller group\r\n\r\n\r\nMonitor closely and adjust in real-time\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Reduces risk of repeating the same mistake.\r\n\r\n7. Communicate Transparently\r\n\r\n\r\nShare what went wrong and what\u2019s being improved\r\n\r\n\r\nShow that decisions are data-driven and student-focused\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Transparency increases stakeholder confidence.\r\n\r\n8. Build a Culture That Accepts Smart Failure\r\n\r\n\r\nEncourage experimentation and innovation\r\n\r\n\r\nMake it safe for teachers to try new methods\r\n\r\n\r\nFocus on continuous improvement, not perfection\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKey Principle\r\nFailure isn\u2019t the problem\u2014failing to learn from it is.\r\nA strong leader turns setbacks into better systems, smarter decisions, and long-term success.\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can convert this into a powerful 1-minute interview answer or a STAR format response so you can confidently deliver it.", "This is a leadership, accountability, and learning-from-failure scenario. The strongest response shows that you own the outcome, learn quickly, and improve the system.\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Take Responsibility (No Blame Game)\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledge that the program didn\u2019t meet expectations\r\n\r\n\r\nCommunicate honestly with staff and stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This builds trust and credibility as a leader.\r\n\r\n2. Analyze What Went Wrong\r\nConduct a structured review:\r\n\r\n\r\nWere the goals unrealistic or unclear?\r\n\r\n\r\nWas there a gap in execution or training?\r\n\r\n\r\nDid we ignore student needs or feedback?\r\n\r\n\r\nWere there resource or time constraints?\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Use data: student performance, feedback, participation rates.\r\n\r\n3. Gather Feedback from All Stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\nTeachers: challenges in implementation\r\n\r\n\r\nStudents: engagement and learning experience\r\n\r\n\r\nParents (if relevant): observed impact\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This gives a 360\u00b0 understanding, not just assumptions.\r\n\r\n4. Identify Key Learnings\r\nConvert failure into insights:\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat worked (keep it)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat didn\u2019t (fix or remove)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat was missing (add it)\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Failure becomes valuable data, not wasted effort.\r\n\r\n5. Make Targeted Improvements\r\n\r\n\r\nRedesign the program based on insights\r\n\r\n\r\nProvide better training/support to teachers\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust content, pacing, or delivery methods\r\n\r\n\r\nStart with a pilot program before full rollout\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Move from trial \u2192 refined strategy.\r\n\r\n6. Re-Implement in Phases\r\n\r\n\r\nTest improvements on a smaller group\r\n\r\n\r\nMonitor closely and adjust in real-time\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Reduces risk of repeating the same mistake.\r\n\r\n7. Communicate Transparently\r\n\r\n\r\nShare what went wrong and what\u2019s being improved\r\n\r\n\r\nShow that decisions are data-driven and student-focused\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Transparency increases stakeholder confidence.\r\n\r\n8. Build a Culture That Accepts Smart Failure\r\n\r\n\r\nEncourage experimentation and innovation\r\n\r\n\r\nMake it safe for teachers to try new methods\r\n\r\n\r\nFocus on continuous improvement, not perfection\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKey Principle\r\nFailure isn\u2019t the problem\u2014failing to learn from it is.\r\nA strong leader turns setbacks into better systems, smarter decisions, and long-term success.\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can convert this into a powerful 1-minute interview answer or a STAR format response so you can confidently deliver it.", "This is a leadership, accountability, and learning-from-failure scenario. The strongest response shows that you own the outcome, learn quickly, and improve the system.\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Take Responsibility (No Blame Game)\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledge that the program didn\u2019t meet expectations\r\n\r\n\r\nCommunicate honestly with staff and stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This builds trust and credibility as a leader.\r\n\r\n2. Analyze What Went Wrong\r\nConduct a structured review:\r\n\r\n\r\nWere the goals unrealistic or unclear?\r\n\r\n\r\nWas there a gap in execution or training?\r\n\r\n\r\nDid we ignore student needs or feedback?\r\n\r\n\r\nWere there resource or time constraints?\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Use data: student performance, feedback, participation rates.\r\n\r\n3. Gather Feedback from All Stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\nTeachers: challenges in implementation\r\n\r\n\r\nStudents: engagement and learning experience\r\n\r\n\r\nParents (if relevant): observed impact\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This gives a 360\u00b0 understanding, not just assumptions.\r\n\r\n4. Identify Key Learnings\r\nConvert failure into insights:\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat worked (keep it)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat didn\u2019t (fix or remove)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat was missing (add it)\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Failure becomes valuable data, not wasted effort.\r\n\r\n5. Make Targeted Improvements\r\n\r\n\r\nRedesign the program based on insights\r\n\r\n\r\nProvide better training/support to teachers\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust content, pacing, or delivery methods\r\n\r\n\r\nStart with a pilot program before full rollout\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Move from trial \u2192 refined strategy.\r\n\r\n6. Re-Implement in Phases\r\n\r\n\r\nTest improvements on a smaller group\r\n\r\n\r\nMonitor closely and adjust in real-time\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Reduces risk of repeating the same mistake.\r\n\r\n7. Communicate Transparently\r\n\r\n\r\nShare what went wrong and what\u2019s being improved\r\n\r\n\r\nShow that decisions are data-driven and student-focused\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Transparency increases stakeholder confidence.\r\n\r\n8. Build a Culture That Accepts Smart Failure\r\n\r\n\r\nEncourage experimentation and innovation\r\n\r\n\r\nMake it safe for teachers to try new methods\r\n\r\n\r\nFocus on continuous improvement, not perfection\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKey Principle\r\nFailure isn\u2019t the problem\u2014failing to learn from it is.\r\nA strong leader turns setbacks into better systems, smarter decisions, and long-term success.\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can convert this into a powerful 1-minute interview answer or a STAR format response so you can confidently deliver it.", "This is a leadership, accountability, and learning-from-failure scenario. The strongest response shows that you own the outcome, learn quickly, and improve the system.\r\nHere\u2019s how I would handle it:\r\n\r\n1. Take Responsibility (No Blame Game)\r\n\r\n\r\nAcknowledge that the program didn\u2019t meet expectations\r\n\r\n\r\nCommunicate honestly with staff and stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This builds trust and credibility as a leader.\r\n\r\n2. Analyze What Went Wrong\r\nConduct a structured review:\r\n\r\n\r\nWere the goals unrealistic or unclear?\r\n\r\n\r\nWas there a gap in execution or training?\r\n\r\n\r\nDid we ignore student needs or feedback?\r\n\r\n\r\nWere there resource or time constraints?\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Use data: student performance, feedback, participation rates.\r\n\r\n3. Gather Feedback from All Stakeholders\r\n\r\n\r\nTeachers: challenges in implementation\r\n\r\n\r\nStudents: engagement and learning experience\r\n\r\n\r\nParents (if relevant): observed impact\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 This gives a 360\u00b0 understanding, not just assumptions.\r\n\r\n4. Identify Key Learnings\r\nConvert failure into insights:\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat worked (keep it)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat didn\u2019t (fix or remove)\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat was missing (add it)\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Failure becomes valuable data, not wasted effort.\r\n\r\n5. Make Targeted Improvements\r\n\r\n\r\nRedesign the program based on insights\r\n\r\n\r\nProvide better training/support to teachers\r\n\r\n\r\nAdjust content, pacing, or delivery methods\r\n\r\n\r\nStart with a pilot program before full rollout\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Move from trial \u2192 refined strategy.\r\n\r\n6. Re-Implement in Phases\r\n\r\n\r\nTest improvements on a smaller group\r\n\r\n\r\nMonitor closely and adjust in real-time\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Reduces risk of repeating the same mistake.\r\n\r\n7. Communicate Transparently\r\n\r\n\r\nShare what went wrong and what\u2019s being improved\r\n\r\n\r\nShow that decisions are data-driven and student-focused\r\n\r\n\r\n\ud83d\udc49 Transparency increases stakeholder confidence.\r\n\r\n8. Build a Culture That Accepts Smart Failure\r\n\r\n\r\nEncourage experimentation and innovation\r\n\r\n\r\nMake it safe for teachers to try new methods\r\n\r\n\r\nFocus on continuous improvement, not perfection\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKey Principle\r\nFailure isn\u2019t the problem\u2014failing to learn from it is.\r\nA strong leader turns setbacks into better systems, smarter decisions, and long-term success.\r\n\r\nIf you want, I can convert this into a powerful 1-minute interview answer or a STAR format response so you can confidently deliver it."]', '{"match_score": "42.17%", "summary": "The responses provided lack depth and relevance to the specific scenarios presented. Many of the answers seem to be copied from a generic template, ignoring the core challenge of each question. The user''s input does not demonstrate a strong understanding of educational administration or the ability to think critically about complex issues. The professionalism and maturity expected in an educational setting are not consistently evident.", "strengths": [], "improvement_areas": ["Develop more tailored responses that address the unique aspects of each scenario", " Demonstrate a clearer understanding of educational administration principles and practices", "Improve the ability to think critically and provide well-reasoned solutions to complex problems"]}'),
	(20, 26, 'Adaptive Explorer', 'Ambivert', 'Exploring', 0.9201496884105576, 'The user''s answers show a mix of preferences for social and solo activities, indicating ambivert tendencies. Their goal status is exploratory, with a desire to learn multiple skills and take a path with high potential. This combination aligns with the Adaptive Explorer category, who are flexible and open to new experiences.', '{"Q1_SocialBattery": "A high-energy concert with a crowd.", "Q2_Communication": "Hopping on a quick, \"face-to-face\" video call.", "Q3_Workspace": "A bustling co-working space with open desks.", "Q4_ProblemSolving": "Digging through Google/Manuals solo.", "Q5_MeetingRole": "The person leading the brainstorm out loud.", "Q6_LearningStyle": "Watching a deep-dive documentary alone.", "Q7_GoalPath": "A winding trail through a beautiful forest.", "Q8_GoalVision": "I have a \"Dream Job\" title in my head.", "Q9_GoalSpeed": "I want to be a \"Jack of all trades\" and know a bit of everything.", "Q10_GoalChoice": "I\u2019d pick the \"Wildcard\" path with high potential."}', 'Above 12th', 'Phase 3 Completed', '{"S1_TheEvent": "A", "S2_TheVariety": "A", "S3_TheInfluence": "B", "S4_TheNewcomer": "A", "S5_TheBrainstorm": "A"}', 'It is fascinating to observe how you navigate complex situations, particularly in scenario S3_TheInfluence, where you chose option B, indicating a nuanced approach to exerting influence and a willingness to consider multiple perspectives. This reveals a thoughtful and collaborative aspect of your Internal Compass, suggesting that your leadership style is characterized by a desire to empower others and foster a sense of community. Your ability to adapt and respond to challenging scenarios with a unique blend of confidence and humility is a testament to your growth potential as a leader. By embracing your natural inclination to explore and learn, you will continue to refine your leadership approach, cultivating a powerful and inspiring presence that motivates others to thrive.', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
	(53, 59, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '10th', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
	(54, 7, 'Strategic Builder', 'Introvert', 'Goal Aware', 0.8317691211298024, 'The user fits the Strategic Builder archetype as they prefer systematic and structured work, plan before execution, and take a leadership role in group decisions, indicating a strong ability to organize and execute plans. Their problem-solving style of trial and error, and preference for interactive sessions and leadership with creative direction, further supports this classification. The user''s ability to focus for hours on a topic and reliance on facts and logic to solve conflicts also aligns with the Strategic Builder archetype.', '{"Tumhe kis type ka kaam zyada pasand hai?": "Systematic aur structured kaam", "Execution preference?": "Main pehle pura plan likhta hoon phir execute karta hoon", "Decision leni ki speed kya hai?": "Main observe karta hoon pehle phir action leta hoon", "Group decision mein tumhara role kya hota hai?": "Leader ban ke final decision leta hoon", "Tumhari problem-solving style kya hai?": "Trial & error", "Tumhe kaunsa learning format sabse zyada pasand hai?": "Interactive sessions/workshops", "Agar team me conflict ho jaye toh tum?": "Facts aur logic se solve karta hoon", "Tumhara ideal creative environment kya hai?": "Leadership + creative direction", "Boredom handling?": "Main ek topic pe ghanto tak focus kar sakta hoon", "Agar aapko confusion ho career me, aap kya karoge?": "Different options try karunga"}', 'Above 12th', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);


